Here's a similar `CompletableFuture` example using a `Student` object:

```java
import java.time.Duration;
import java.util.concurrent.CompletableFuture;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;

// Student record
record Student(int id, String name, String grade) {}

public class StudentCompletableFuture {

    private static final Logger log = LoggerFactory.getLogger(StudentCompletableFuture.class);

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        log.info("main starts");

        var cf = fetchStudentFromDB(101);
        cf.thenAccept(student -> 
            log.info("Student received => id={}, name={}, grade={}", 
                student.id(), student.name(), student.grade())
        );

        log.info("main ends");
        CommonUtils.sleep(Duration.ofSeconds(3));
    }

    // Simulates an instant/cached student lookup
    private static CompletableFuture<Student> fetchStudentFromCache(int id) {
        log.info("fetchStudentFromCache starts");
        var cf = new CompletableFuture<Student>();
        cf.complete(new Student(id, "Alice", "A"));
        log.info("fetchStudentFromCache ends");
        return cf;
    }

    // Simulates a slow DB call using a virtual thread
    private static CompletableFuture<Student> fetchStudentFromDB(int id) {
        log.info("fetchStudentFromDB starts");
        var cf = new CompletableFuture<Student>();
        Thread.ofVirtual().start(() -> {
            log.info("Fetching student from DB...");
            CommonUtils.sleep(Duration.ofSeconds(2)); // simulate DB delay
            cf.complete(new Student(id, "Bob", "B+"));
            log.info("DB fetch complete");
        });
        log.info("fetchStudentFromDB ends");
        return cf;
    }
}
```

**Expected Output:**
```
main starts
fetchStudentFromDB starts
fetchStudentFromDB ends
main ends
Fetching student from DB...       ← happens in virtual thread
DB fetch complete
Student received => id=101, name=Bob, grade=B+
```

**Key differences from the original:**
- `String` is replaced with a `Student` record containing `id`, `name`, and `grade`
- Two methods show a **cache hit** (instant) vs **DB fetch** (slow/async)
- The `thenAccept` callback now logs all student fields
- Uses Java 16+ `record` for clean, immutable data modeling

Requires **Java 21+** and the same `CommonUtils` and SLF4J setup as before.
